{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493399","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493399"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:09:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:09:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1312"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1312","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1312"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.09,0.62,0.01,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1312"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44628"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1312","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1312"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1312"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29507"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"697"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"528"},{"type":"contributions","id":"555"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8745"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42284"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44628","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44628"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman is brought in to the Emergency Department by her family who found her unconscious at home with large wounds across her wrist. She has since been medically stabilised with her wound sutured. The nurse looking after her reports that the patient has been irritable, easily frustrated with staff with temper outbursts and often teary about her recent relationship breakdown. Her medical history includes 3 low-lethality suicidal attempts in the past year. Since her last discharge 6 months ago, she has been attending weekly individual and group sessions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following treatments is she most likely to have received?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cognitive behavioural therapy","Supportive psychotherapy","Dialectical behaviour therapy","Eye movement desensitisation and reprocessing therapy","Attachment-based psychotherapy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBorderline personality disorder \u003C/strong\u003E(BPD) is characterised by a pervasive pattern of instability of interpersonal relationships, self-image affective regulation and marked impulsivity. This is seen in this patient with multiple self-harm attempts, inappropriate anger and relationship breakdowns. The mainstay treatment for BPD is \u003Cstrong\u003Edialectical behaviour therapy (DBT\u003C/strong\u003E). DBT is an evidence-based psychotherapy that focuses on behavioural analysis, distress tolerance skills, interpersonal skills, mindfulness and emotional regulation training. This therapy consists of weekly individual psychotherapy and group skills training that last for approximately one year.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECognitive-behavioural therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is also utilised in BPD psychotherapy. However, the evidence for its efficacy has mixed results. CBT has level 1 evidence for treatment of mild-moderate depressive episodes. Additionally, very useful for anxiety disorders.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESupportive therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is widely used in medical practice to help patients deal with a crisis such as coping with an illness. It is not as effective as DBT.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAttachment-based therapy\u003C/strong\u003E looks at the connection between an infant\u0027s early attachment experiences with their primary caregivers, which aims to rebuild a trusting and supportive relationship.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEye movement desensitisation and reprocessing therapy (EMDR)\u003C/strong\u003E is used for post-traumatic stress disorder, not BPD.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Dialectical behavioural therapy is first-line psychotherapy for borderline personality disorder"],"references":["Davidson K, Norrie J, Tyrer P, et al. The effectiveness of cognitive behavior therapy for borderline personality disorder: results from the borderline personality disorder study of cognitive therapy (BOSCOT) trial. J Pers Disord 2006; 20:450.","Cristea IA, Gentili C, Cotet CD, et al. Efficacy of Psychotherapies for Borderline Personality Disorder: A Systematic Review and Meta-analysis. JAMA Psychiatry 2017; 74:319.","Malhi GS, Bassett D, Boyce P, et al. Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Psychiatrists clinical practice guidelines for mood disorders. ANZJP 2015; 49(12) 1-185"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29507"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1312"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29507","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/29507"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-04-24T21:37:51+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-02T09:52:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1312"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44628"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66"